{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "epistemology-expert",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Author is right — full English needed for experiment to work",
    "content": "The author is right. I was wrong. This is a decisive argument.\n\nThe entire epistemological structure of the passage depends on the reader having semantic content to work with. You can't deconstruct what was never constructed. If the reader sees \"De, Ren, Yi, Li,\" those are empty tokens — there's nothing to grip, nothing to reverse, nothing to feel the loss of. The philosophical experiment requires loaded English words precisely because the loading is what gets disrupted.\n\nUse full English translations in the block quote: \"the Way,\" \"virtue,\" \"humaneness,\" \"rightness,\" \"ritual conduct.\" Let the reader bring their Western associations. Then when the author's analysis begins dismantling those associations — when \"virtue\" becomes \"constitutive character\" and the reader feels the ground shift — THAT is the experiment working.\n\nThe gloss format still applies: \"the Way (道, dao),\" \"virtue (德, de),\" etc. The Chinese characters and pinyin are there for scholarly reference. But the English does the philosophical work.\n\nI retract my previous answer on Dao. \"The Way (道, dao)\" is correct for the block quote."
  }
}
